{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T12:37:56.661227+00:00", "modified": "2025-02-06T21:19:56.105428+00:00", "id": 13479433, "conceptrecid": "13479432", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479433", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479432", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13479433", "metadata": {"title": "Spatial and land\u2010use determinants of bat species richness, functional diversity, and site uniqueness throughout the largest Tropical country, Brazil", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13479433", "publication_date": "2022", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Abstract\n            \n              \n                \n                  Bats are one of the most species\u2010rich mammal groups in the Tropics. This highly radiated group embodies many distinct ecomorphological traits, prompting their functional diversity. Furthermore, bat assemblages typically have high beta\u2010diversity due to distinctive compositions across geographic gradients.\n                \n                \n                  We aimed to understand the distribution of multifaceted bat diversity metrics (i.e. species richness, functional richness, Rao's quadratic entropy, and local contribution to beta\u2010diversity) as a function of land\u2010cover variables, environmental productivity and complexity, and anthropogenic features in the largest Tropical country worldwide: Brazil.\n                \n                \n                  We gathered data on bat distribution based on empirical published datasets and embodied the assemblages at the metacommunity scale, based on 10\u2010km radial clusters. We obtained spatial data on land cover, gross primary production, vegetation height, and human population density for the same radial clusters. We analysed the data via diversity metrics, descriptive statistics, and generalised additive models.\n                \n                \n                  Our results showed that two main metaregions (central\u2010western Amazon and the Atlantic coast) embrace the largest richness of bat species. The major positive predictor of bat diversity metrics was vegetation height. Bat diversity metrics throughout Brazil were also significantly influenced by agriculture (negatively) and urban cover (partially positively).\n                \n                \n                  We can conclude that bat diversity is more predictable from vegetation height and landscape features \u2013 especially agriculture and urban cover \u2013 at the metacommunity scale, whereas functional and local contributions to beta\u2010diversity metrics are more predictable from spatial autocorrelations, with some biome\u2010induced constrained effects. For the conservation of Brazilian bats and the many ecosystem services they provide, it is absolutely essential to prevent the further collapse of Brazilian biomes that is currently ongoing and fuelled by landscape changes, expansion of agribusiness frontiers, deforestation, and fires.\n                \n              \n            \n          , \n            RESUMO EM PORTUGU\u00caS\n            \n              \n                \n                  Os morcegos s\u00e3o um dos grupos de mam\u00edferos mais ricos em esp\u00e9cies nos tr\u00f3picos. Este grupo altamente radiado incorpora muitos e distintos tra\u00e7os ecomorfol\u00f3gicos, incrementando sua diversidade funcional. Al\u00e9m disso, as assembleias de morcegos normalmente t\u00eam alta diversidade beta devido a composi\u00e7\u00f5es distintas ao longo dos gradientes geogr\u00e1ficos.\n                \n                \n                  Nosso objetivo foi compreender a distribui\u00e7\u00e3o de \u00edndices de diversidade de morcegos (i.e. riqueza de esp\u00e9cies, riqueza funcional, entropia quadr\u00e1tica de Rao e contribui\u00e7\u00e3o local para a diversidade beta) em fun\u00e7\u00e3o de vari\u00e1veis de uso e cobertura do solo, produtividade e complexidade ambiental e de caracter\u00edsticas antropog\u00eanicas no maior pa\u00eds tropical do mundo: o Brasil.\n                \n                \n                  \n                    Reunimos dados sobre a distribui\u00e7\u00e3o de morcegos com base em conjuntos de dados emp\u00edricos j\u00e1 publicados e incorporamos as assembleias em escala de metacomunidades, com base em aglomerados radiais (\n                    buffers\n                    ) de 10\u00a0km. Obtivemos dados espaciais sobre cobertura do solo, produ\u00e7\u00e3o prim\u00e1ria bruta, altura da vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o e densidade da popula\u00e7\u00e3o humana para os mesmos\n                    buffers\n                    . Analisamos os dados por meio de m\u00e9tricas de diversidade, estat\u00edsticas descritivas e modelos aditivos generalizados.\n                  \n                \n                \n                  Nossos resultados mostraram que duas meta\u2010regi\u00f5es (Amaz\u00f4nia central\u2010ocidental e costa atl\u00e2ntica) incorporam a maior riqueza de esp\u00e9cies de morcegos. O principal preditor positivo das m\u00e9tricas de diversidade de morcegos foi a altura da vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o. As m\u00e9tricas de diversidade de morcegos em todo o Brasil tamb\u00e9m foram significativamente influenciadas pela agricultura (negativamente) e cobertura urbana (parcialmente positiva).\n                \n                \n                  Podemos concluir que a diversidade de morcegos na escala da metacomunidade \u00e9 mais previs\u00edvel a partir da altura da vegeta\u00e7\u00e3o e caracter\u00edsticas da paisagem \u2014 especialmente agricultura e cobertura urbana \u2014, enquanto as contribui\u00e7\u00f5es funcionais e locais para m\u00e9tricas de diversidade beta s\u00e3o mais previs\u00edveis por autocorrela\u00e7\u00f5es espaciais, tendo efeitos induzidos pelos diferentes biomas. Para a conserva\u00e7\u00e3o dos morcegos no Brasil \u2014 e os muitos servi\u00e7os ecossist\u00eamicos que eles fornecem \u2014 \u00e9 absolutamente essencial prevenir um colapso ainda maior do que j\u00e1 vem ocorrendo atualmente nos biomas brasileiros, e que \u00e9 fortemente alimentado por mudan\u00e7as na paisagem, expans\u00e3o das fronteiras do agroneg\u00f3cio, desmatamento e inc\u00eandios.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Bogoni, Juliano A.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Carvalho\u2010Rocha, V\u00edtor", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Da Silva, Pedro Giov\u00e2ni", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/1be3fe04611f45b3ca1149186ca3a26e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/87b5a409e9c1c99334c53633e4b45cdce3d2a5638b7ef963db245dfa054659c1", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/ZWYJ85EY", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/ZWYJ85EY", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/2d314c0abf7fc658ad1a3e60f60da302!/b305670-308140", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/ce1e7618f237ff56e74d51f496e811a3", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "2", "pages": "267-283", "title": "Mammal Review", "volume": "52"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/1be3fe04611f45b3ca1149186ca3a26e"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:ZWYJ85EY"}, {"identifier": "10.1111/mam.12279"}], "communities": [{"id": "batlit"}, {"id": "biosyslit"}], "relations": {"